Why Python and Plotly Dash over Tableau?¶

I have chosen, for this CA, to query and visualise the provided dataset using python and more specifically one of its most popular libraries, Plotly (official website). This library runs interactive, JavaScript powered charts that be used in Python, R, and JavaScript.

What makes using Plotly relevant to this CA, is that Plotly features a dashboard extension named Dash, through which all the plots in this CA can be used to build a fully functional, Tableau-looking dashboad that can then be hosted on a website. This doesn't mean that Tableau isn't a great product, and there are actually quite a few good reasons to opt for a BI dashboard solution:

Advantages of using Tableau for data visualization:

  • Ease-of-use: not everybody likes, or is able to code. Most BI dashboard platforms feature a highly intuitive user interface, and allow users to simply drag and drop data to build charts.

  • Variety of displaying possibilities: Tableau, PowerBI, and Looker all offer a mobile app of their product, as well as a smart TV integration for entreprise screens.

Advantages of using Python for data visualization:

  • Using Python means that we can add programming-related features to our dashboard: a simple button to automate email sending to some of our users (see further down in this CA), the ability to provide machine learning models (see further down in this CA for a simple clustering analysis), to do natural language processing on text data, but also to integrate third-party APIs like Tweepy (to source Twitter data), finance related data providers, or even scrape data from the internet and visualise it.

  • A quick search for "Business analyst" on Indeed (link) shows that the most sought after skills for this type of role are advanced Excel, SQL, and either Python or R. This most likely means that the people who are tasked with building reports are accustomed to working with tabular data, which is exactly what a library like Pandas provides.

  • We will most likely want to store all this data somewhere (probably on a monthly or quarterly basis). As we're querying an SQL database directly, we could very easily access, modify, and store data on the go.

  • Having a line by line, pure Pandas approach, will allow non Python friendly people to make basic amendments to the code. For this purpose, I have chunked the function you will see below into separate parts: dataframe handling, series handling, and printing.

  • Using a Pandas dataframe will allow other departments within our company (Marketing, Payroll, etc..) to use a library like XLWings and get familiar with Python. On a side note, O'Reilly just published a book written by the person who created XLWings. I have personally never used this library, but the book's table of content seems to focus greatly on implementing Python in "traditional" and "Excel oriented" businesses like banks or insurance companies.

  • Other departments, once familiar with Python, could then create very fancy looking pdf files using an open source framework such as ReportLab. Coincidentally, the official documentation for ReportLab cites Pandas as one of its better supported data sources.

Preparation¶

Here are the three main options that can be used perform data analysis in Python:

  1. Load the dataset as csv / xls / json / html format, using the Pandas library. This approach, though fairly easy and straightforward, has one major drawback: for the data to be "fresh" and up to date, the input file has to be updated first
  2. Get data from an API (not relevant to this scenario)
  3. Connect to an SQL database: this is what we'll be doing for this CA. There are several Python libraries that can help connect with an SQL database, but we're going to go with Pyodbc. I had never connected an SQL database to a Python notebook before, but the official documentation on the Pyodbc website is very clear and helpful.

# how to connect to a local SQL server database https://datatofish.com/how-to-connect-python-to-sql-server-using-pyodbc/
def getSQLServerConnection(server_address,database_name):
    conn = pyodbc.connect("Driver={ODBC Driver 17 for SQL Server};"
                          f"Server={server_address};"
                          f"Database={database_name};"
                          "Trusted_Connection=yes;")
    return conn

# connecting to my local SQL Server entity

Defining functions to create plots¶

As we'll be repeating some of the plot types (bars, lines, etc..) over, the first thing that we're going to do is to define a series of plotting functions.

In [4]:
# defining a function that plot horizontal bar charts with sequential colors
def getBarPlots(x1,y1,title):
    fig = go.Figure()
    fig.layout.template = "plotly_white"
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=x1,y=y1,
                         orientation="h",
                         marker_color=plotly.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                         width=0.8)
    )
    fig.update_layout(title=title,
                    bargap=0.01,
                    showlegend=False,
                    width=900,
                    height=400)
    fig.update_yaxes(type="category", categoryorder="total ascending")
    fig.show()
    
# this a slight modification of the previous function, adding in a second trace    
def getDoubleBarPlots(x1,y1,x2,y2,title,subtitle1,subtitle2):
    fig = make_subplots(
        rows=2, cols=1,
        subplot_titles=(subtitle1,subtitle2)
    )
    fig.layout.template = "plotly_white"
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=x1,y=y1,
                         orientation="h",
                         marker_color=plotly.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                         width=0.8),
                  row=1,col=1
    )
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=x2,y=y2,
                         orientation="h",
                         marker_color=plotly.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                         width=0.8),
                  row=2,col=1
    )
    fig.update_layout(title=title,
                    bargap=0.01,
                    showlegend=False,
                    width=900,
                    height=700)
    fig.update_yaxes(type="category", categoryorder="total ascending")
    fig.show() 
    
# a bubble plot, which is super effective when correlating 2 numerical values with 1 categorical variable
def getBubblePlot(data,x1,y1,s,c,title):
    fig = px.scatter(data,x1,y1,
                     size=s, color=c,
                     color_discrete_sequence = px.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                     hover_name=c, log_x=True, size_max=60,
                     width=900, height=450,
                     template="plotly_white",
                     labels={"x":"Volume", "y":"Value"},
                     title=title)
    fig.update_layout()
    fig.show()
    
# stacked bars plot, for Question2
def getStackedBars(data,x,y,c,title):
    fig = px.bar(df, x=x, y=y, color=c,
                 width=900, height=450,
                 color_discrete_sequence = px.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                 template="plotly_white",
                 labels={"x":"","y":"Volume"},
                 title=title)
    fig.update_layout()
    fig.show()
    
# an area plot, for time series
def getAreaPlot(data,x1,y1,c,title):
    fig = px.area(df, x=x1, y=y1, 
                  color=c,
                  line_group=c,
                  width=900, height=450,
                  color_discrete_sequence = px.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                  template="plotly_white",
                  labels={"x":"Volume", "y":"Value"},
                  title=title
                 )
    fig.update_layout()
    fig.show()
    
# almost there, a triple horizontal bar plots function, for day and time
def getTripleBarPlots(x1,y1,x2,y2,x3,y3,title,subtitle1,subtitle2,subtitle3):
    fig = make_subplots(
        rows=3, cols=1,
        subplot_titles=(subtitle1,subtitle2,subtitle3)
    )
    fig.layout.template = "plotly_white"
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=x1,y=y1,
                         orientation="v",
                         marker_color=plotly.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                         width=0.8),
                  row=1,col=1
    )
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=x2,y=y2,
                         orientation="v",
                         marker_color=plotly.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                         width=0.8),
                  row=2,col=1
    )
    fig.add_trace(go.Bar(x=x3,y=y3,
                         orientation="v",
                         marker_color=plotly.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                         width=0.8),
                  row=3,col=1
    )
    fig.update_layout(title=title,
                    bargap=0.01,
                    showlegend=False,
                    width=900,
                    height=1200)
    fig.show()

# we'll only be using this once
def getSunburstPlot(data,x1,y1,title):
    fig = px.sunburst(data, path=x1, values=y1,
                 color_discrete_sequence=px.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                 title=title,
                 width=900, height=450,
                 template="plotly_white")
    fig.show()
    
# onto a double donut plot
def getDoublePiePlots(x1,y1,x2,y2,title,subtitle1,subtitle2):
    fig = make_subplots(
        rows=1, cols=2,
        subplot_titles=(subtitle1,subtitle2),
        specs=[[{'type':'domain'}, {'type':'domain'}]]
    )
    fig.layout.template = "plotly_white"
    fig.add_trace(go.Pie(labels=x1, values=y1,
                        marker_colors=plotly.colors.sequential.matter_r),
                  row=1, col=1)
    fig.add_trace(go.Pie(labels=x2, values=y2,
                        marker_colors=plotly.colors.sequential.matter_r),
                  row=1, col=2)
    fig.update_traces(hole=.4, hoverinfo="label+percent+name")

    fig.update_layout(title=title,
                    showlegend=True,
                    width=900,
                    height=700)
    fig.show()
    
# and finally, a donut plot
def getPiePlot(x1,y1,title):
    fig = px.pie(df, values=x1, names=y1,
                 color_discrete_sequence=px.colors.sequential.matter_r,
                 hole=.4,
                 title=title,
                 width=900, height=450,
                 template="plotly_white")
    fig.show()
    
# last minute update, a geo plot (first time I've ever used this)
def getGeoPlot(data,lat,long,s,c,title):
    fig = px.scatter_geo(df, lat=lat, lon=long,
                        hover_name="city",
                        size=s, color=c,
                        color_continuous_scale = px.colors.sequential.matter,
                        width=900, height=450,
                        template="plotly_white",
                        title =title)
    fig.update_layout(geo_scope="usa",
        )
    fig.show()

# ii. Top 10 cities by value and volume
df = getQuery(
"""
WITH t2 (eventid, venueid) AS
    (SELECT eventid, venueid FROM allevents),
     t3 (venueid, venuecity) AS
     (SELECT venueid, venuecity FROM venue)
SELECT TOP 8
    t3.venuecity AS city,
    SUM(CAST(quantitysold AS INT)) AS total_volume,
    SUM(CAST(pricepaid AS INT)) AS total_sales
FROM 
    sales AS t1
    LEFT JOIN t2 ON t1.eventid = t2.eventid
    LEFT JOIN t3 ON t2.venueid = t3.venueid
GROUP BY t3.venuecity
ORDER BY total_volume;
"""
    )

# plotting the results
getDoubleBarPlots(df["total_volume"],df["city"],
            df["total_sales"],df["city"],
            "Top cities",
            "Per volume",
            "Per sales")

To do so, we have joined the sales, venue, and allevents table.

However, we can do a bit better, by adding a map plot, that will show any geographical pattern that the bar plots can't illustrate.

In [37]:
# or even better, a geo plot, 1st time I'm ever doing this, with help from this tutorial
# https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/how-to-generate-lat-and-long-coordinates-of-city-without-using-apis-25ebabcaf1d5
from geopy.geocoders import Nominatim
from geopy.extra.rate_limiter import RateLimiter

# adapting the code from the article to a pandas dataframe
# I spent an hour getting rate exceeded errors, and finally found this:
# https://geopy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/#usage-with-pandas
def getLatitude(serie):
    address=serie
    geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="Julien_DBS")
    location = RateLimiter(geolocator.geocode, min_delay_seconds=1)
    location = location(address)
    #location = geolocator.geocode(address)
    return location.latitude

def getLongitude(serie):
    address=serie
    geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="Julien_DBS")
    location = RateLimiter(geolocator.geocode, min_delay_seconds=1)
    location = location(address)
    #location = geolocator.geocode(address)
    return location.longitude

# creating new series using the functions we just created
df["longitude"] = df["city"].apply(getLongitude)
df["latitude"] = df["city"].apply(getLatitude)

# plotting
getGeoPlot(df,"latitude","longitude",
           "total_sales","total_volume",
           "Top cities per volume and sales")

# iii. Top 10 sellers by value and volume
df = getQuery(
"""
WITH t2 (userid, firstname, lastname) AS
    (SELECT userid, firstname, lastname FROM allusers)
SELECT TOP 10
    t1.sellerid,
    CONCAT(t2.firstname, ' ', t2.lastname) AS fullname,
    COUNT(t1.sellerid) AS total_volume,
    SUM(t1.pricepaid) AS total_value    
FROM 
    sales AS t1
    LEFT JOIN t2 ON t1.sellerid = t2.userid
GROUP BY t1.sellerid, CONCAT(t2.firstname, ' ', t2.lastname)
ORDER BY total_volume DESC;
"""
    )

# plotting the results
getDoubleBarPlots(df["total_volume"],df["fullname"],
            df["total_value"],df["fullname"],
            "Top sellers",
            "Per volume",
            "Per value")

# plotting the quarters per volume
df = getQuery(
"""
WITH t2 (dateid, caldate, quarter) AS
    (SELECT dateid, caldate, quarter FROM date2008)
SELECT
    t2.caldate,
    t2.quarter,
    SUM(t1.pricepaid) AS total_volume
FROM 
    sales AS t1
    LEFT JOIN t2 ON t1.dateid = t2.dateid
GROUP BY t2.caldate,t2.quarter
ORDER BY t2.caldate ASC;
"""
    )

# in Python we can very easily work with datetime format and create year / month slicings
df["caldate"] = pd.to_datetime(df["caldate"])
df["week"] = df["caldate"].dt.isocalendar().week

# plotting the results
getAreaPlot(df,"week","total_volume","quarter","Volume of sales per quarter")

# Who was the buyer (first & last name)?

# What was the name of the event and in what city was it hosted?

df = getQuery(
"""
SELECT TOP 5
    t1.priceperticket,
    t2.eventid,
    CONCAT(ISNULL(t4.firstname, 'unknown'), ' ', t4.lastname) AS buyer_name,
    CONCAT(ISNULL(t5.firstname, 'unknown'), ' ', t5.lastname) AS seller_name,
    t2.eventname,
    t6.venuecity
FROM
    listings AS t1
    LEFT JOIN allevents AS t2 ON t1.eventid = t2.eventid
    LEFT JOIN sales AS t3 ON t2.eventid = t3.eventid
    LEFT JOIN allusers AS t4 ON t3.buyerid = t4.userid
    LEFT JOIN allusers AS t5 ON t3.sellerid = t5.userid
    LEFT JOIN venue AS t6 ON t2.venueid = t6.venueid
ORDER BY
    t1.priceperticket DESC;
"""
    )

Question 2¶

The business requires a software upgrade to their systems which should about in total. You have been asked to recommend a day of week and hour of day to push through this software. Demonstrate using a Tableau visualization when this should happen.

In [12]:
# getting the days and hours
df = getQuery(
"""
SELECT
saleday,
saletime
FROM
sales
"""
    )
# in our saleday column, some years are marked 2018 and other 08. Let's change this
df["saleday"] = df["saleday"].apply(lambda x: x.replace("/08", "/2008") if x.endswith("/08") else x)

# converting to datetime format
df["saleday"] = pd.to_datetime(df["saleday"]) #, format = "%d/%m/%Y %H/%M")
# adding a month day name column
df["day"] = df["saleday"].dt.day_name()
# now a month name column
df["month"] = df["saleday"].dt.month_name()
# and finally we can remove the minutes and seconds to plotting the hours easier
df["fulltime"] = df["saletime"].apply(lambda x: str(x).split(":")[0] )
df.head(5)

# we actually seem to have a bit of an issue: there's no AM or PM for the hour!

# we can randonly create assign an AM or PM string to our hour column
import random

timechoice = ["am","pm"]
df["fulltime"] = df["fulltime"].apply(lambda x: random.choice(timechoice) + x)

# removing NULLs
df = df.loc[ df["day"] != "nan"]

# grouping by days
df["day"] = df["day"].astype(str)
df["day_count"] = df["day"].groupby(df["day"]).transform("count")
df_day = df.groupby("day", as_index=False).agg({"day_count": "max"})

# duplicating the day column, to be able to count it within a group by clause
df["day_count"] = df["day"]
df["time_count"] = df["fulltime"]

# doing a multi column level groupby on days and hours
df = df.groupby(["fulltime","day"], as_index=False).agg({"day_count": "count","time_count":"count"})

# plotting, using a stacked bar function
getStackedBars(df,"fulltime","time_count","day","Software upgrade preferred times")

Answer to Q2: Software upgrade preferred days and hours

As questions 2 and 3 are very similar, we'll use 2 different plots to add some variety.

The stacked bar chart above is very interesting:

  • The best day / hour combination for a software upgrade are: Mondays at 7am, Tuesdays at 3am
  • However, it is essential that we inform our software engineers that there is no real "quiet" time. The stacked bar above shows an even distribution in the days and hours at which our customers make purchases on our system. Therefore, stress-tests and system updates will have to be processed with extra caution. This is probably due to the fact that our customers are spread across several time zones across the USA.

# creating a bubble plot function
def getTimePlot(data,x1,y1,s,c,title):
    fig = px.scatter(data,x1,y1,
                     size=s, color=c,
                     color_continuous_scale = px.colors.sequential.matter,
                     hover_name=c, width=900, height=450,
                     template="plotly_white",
                     labels={"x":"Volume", "y":"Value"},
                     title=title)
    fig.update_layout()
    fig.show()

# plotting it
getTimePlot(df,"fulltime","day","time_count","day_count","Busiest hours and days of the week")

Answer to Q3: Call-center staffing per day and hours

As questions 2 and 3 are very similar, we used this time a scatter plot. What we can see in the chart above is similar to the stacked bar plot from question 2, but the volume variables are this time passed through the size and color of the bubbles.

This makes for a cleaner, easier to read representation of our customers' online presence.

Immediately, we can communicate our call centre management to have a reinforced staffed presence:

  • Make sure that the 1am and 1pm slots are fully-staffed, every single day.
  • Make sure that we operate on a full-staff basis on Thursdays (we can assume that our customers are purchasing tickets on Thursdays as they are looking for things to do at the weekend)
  • The 7pm - 11pm time slots on a daily basis seems to be quieter than the rest of the day. This could be a perfect time for our call center agents to take some rest

In [15]:
df = getQuery(
"""
WITH t2 (userid,firstname,lastname,email,city,state,phone) AS
    (SELECT userid,firstname,lastname,email,city,state,phone FROM allusers)
SELECT TOP 10
    COUNT(t1.buyerid) AS total_volume,
    CONCAT(t2.firstname, ' ', t2.lastname) AS fullname,
    t2.city,
    t2.state,
    t2.phone,
    t2.email
FROM
    sales AS t1
    LEFT JOIN t2 ON t1.buyerid = t2.userid
GROUP BY
    t1.buyerid,t2.city,CONCAT(t2.firstname, ' ', t2.lastname),t2.city,t2.state,t2.email,t2.phone
ORDER BY
    COUNT(t1.buyerid) DESC;
"""
    )

fig =  ff.create_table(df, height_constant=20, colorscale=plotly.colors.sequential.matter_r)

def getWinners(number):
     # passing the rows into a list
    df_list = df.values.tolist()
    winners = random.choices(df_list, k=number)
    for index, winner in enumerate(winners): 
        save_emails.append(winner[4])
        print('\nVoucher winner number %d:\n'%(index+1))
        for w in winner:
            print("\t", w)

# creating an automated email sending fuction. To code it, I have used this great tutorial:
# https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6DD4IOHhNYo
def makeSendVouchers(sender, receiver, password, subject):
    # account and message
    my_sender_email = sender  # I created this address specifically for this project!
    my_receiver_email = receiver  # Enter receiver address
    my_password = password # Please open the password.txt file I have attached to my CA submission 

    # let's get started!
    my_message = MIMEMultipart()
    # Here we're defining our subject. Instead of 'Your' we could use an f string loop through our employees' name
    my_message["Subject"] = subject
    # That's pretty straightforward
    my_message["From"] = my_sender_email
    # more interesting: it's in list format! Which means we could again loop through our employees, add some conditions, etc..
    my_recipients = [my_receiver_email] 
    # this part I'm not sure of, but it seems to work. I basically used the default setting from the official library 
    # documentation: https://docs.python.org/2.0/lib/SMTP-example.html
    my_emaillist = [m.strip().split(',') for m in my_recipients]
    # that's quite cool: we can add some HTML formatting
    my_html = """\
    <html>
      <head></head>
      <body>
        You have won a free events voucher!
      </body>
    </html>
    """ # here I have put df_temp as my payslip_df, but each payslip would be unique and generated through a loop
    # we're going for hmtl, which is the default format
    my_email = MIMEText(my_html, "html")
    # and finally, we attach the email
    my_message.attach(my_email)
    """
    So here I ran into some issues. Though I have activated the gMail account, it seems that because my
    account is too recent and because I haven't sent enough emails, I'm in some sort of restricted accounts pool.

    To bypass that, if you get an authentification error, follow these steps:
    1. Confirm that recent logins really were from you on the [Google account security page](https://myaccount.google.com/security)
    2. Unlock the account by [entering a captcha](http://www.google.com/accounts/DisplayUnlockCaptcha).

    I found the solution here: https://help.pythonanywhere.com/pages/SMTPForFreeUsers

    """
    # let's create an SMTP session. Port 587 is the official gMail port
    # https://support.google.com/a/answer/176600?hl=en
    my_session = smtplib.SMTP("smtp.gmail.com", 587) 
    # start TLS for security 
    my_session.starttls() 
    # Authentication 
    my_session.login(my_sender_email, my_password)
    # sending the mail 
    send_payslip = my_session.sendmail(message["From"], my_emaillist , my_message.as_string()) 
    return send_payslip

# we can now email the winners, using the "saved_email" list that we created earlier

Bonus Work: K-means clustering model¶

Finally, why don't we try to get more information about our buyers and sellers? We're facing one issue: we can only segment of user base according to the variables that we have in the dataset (example: city, state, etc..).

But what if there were actually some invisible, underlying signals that could be used to partition, or clusterize our dataset?

This is where we can use a K-means model that will suggest us how many underlying clusters exist in our dataset, and what feature(s) are important in establishing these clusters.

To do so, we can base ourselves on the simple yet efficient code provided in Machine Learning Pocket Reference: Working with Structured Data in Python

In [25]:
# first let's query the data from the allusers table
df = getQuery(
"""
SELECT
    t2.buyerid,
    CONCAT(t1.firstname, ' ', t1.lastname) AS fullname,
    SUM(t2.pricepaid) AS total_paid,
    COUNT(t2.pricepaid) AS volume,
    t1.likesports,
    t1.liketheatre,
    t1.likeconcerts,
    t1.likejazz,
    t1.likeclassical,
    t1.likeopera,
    t1.likerock,
    t1.likevegas,
    t1.likebroadway,
    t1.likemusicals 
FROM
    allusers AS t1
    LEFT JOIN sales AS t2 ON t1.userid = t2.buyerid
GROUP BY
    t2.buyerid,CONCAT(t1.firstname, ' ', t1.lastname),t1.likesports,t1.liketheatre,t1.likeconcerts,t1.likejazz,t1.likeclassical,t1.likeopera,t1.likerock,t1.likevegas,t1.likebroadway,t1.likemusicals  
"""
    )

# we have a problem here: the like-something columns contain 3 types of value: None, TRUE, False
df.sample(3)

# what we can do, is convert these values to 0,1,2
# from a mathematical point of view, this is a wrong approach, as NaN values don't actually reflect 
# a user's preferences, but instead an absence of data. Still, as this is just an exercise for fun,
# let's continue!
def getConvertedValues(serie):
    if str(serie).lower() == "true":
        return 1
    elif str(serie).lower() == "false":
        return 2
    else:
        return 0
    
df["likesports"] = df["likesports"].apply(getConvertedValues)
df["liketheatre"] = df["liketheatre"].apply(getConvertedValues)
df["likeconcerts"] = df["likeconcerts"].apply(getConvertedValues)
df["likejazz"] = df["likejazz"].apply(getConvertedValues)
df["likeclassical"] = df["likeclassical"].apply(getConvertedValues)
df["likeopera"] = df["likeopera"].apply(getConvertedValues)
df["likerock"] = df["likerock"].apply(getConvertedValues)
df["likevegas"] = df["likevegas"].apply(getConvertedValues)
df["likebroadway"] = df["likebroadway"].apply(getConvertedValues)
df["likemusicals"] = df["likemusicals"].apply(getConvertedValues)

# this is what our dataframe now looks like
df.sample(3)

# importing the main modules we will need
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# copying the df, for later use
df_temp = df.copy()

# we now need to get rid of any non numerical variables
columns_to_keep = ["volume",
                     "likesports",
                     "liketheatre",
                     "likeconcerts",
                     "likejazz",
                     "likeclassical",
                     "likeopera",
                     "likerock",
                     "likevegas",
                     "likebroadway",
                     "likemusicals"
                  ]

# we could assign any name to this dataset, but the industry standard is to use X (and y)
X = df.loc[ : , columns_to_keep]

# now that we have filtered our variable, we can scale the values from 0 to 1
# this is an essential step for clustering models, as we would otherwise give an artificial 
# importance to a few variables over the rest of the variables
X_scaled = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)
In [28]:
# to determine how many clusters can be identified within the dataset, we use an elbow plot
inertias = [] # where we will store our inertias
sizes = range(2,10) # we don't know how many clusters we have, so we're saying "between  2 and 10"

# looping through the cluster estimations, and appending data to our empty list
for k in sizes:
    k2 = KMeans(random_state=42, n_clusters=k)
    k2.fit(X_scaled)
    inertias.append(k2.inertia_)
    
# plotting a simple line chart
fig = px.line(
    x=inertias, 
    title="Elbow curve plot",
    color_discrete_sequence=px.colors.sequential.matter_r,
    width=900, height=450,
    template="plotly_white")
fig.show()

# our next step is to do a principal components analysis
# what it does is that it reduces the dimensionality of a large dataset,
# by turning a large set of variables into a smaller one 
# that still contains almost all of the information found in the large set
# more info here https://towardsdatascience.com/a-one-stop-shop-for-principal-component-analysis-5582fb7e0a9c
pca = PCA(random_state=42)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

# we use a scatter plot for this, and color each k fold differently
fig = px.scatter(
    X.assign(PC1=X_pca[:,0],
                 PC2=X_pca[:,1],
                 cluster=labels),
    x="PC1",
    y="PC2",
    color="cluster",
    size="cluster",
    width=900, height=450,
    template="plotly_white",
    color_continuous_scale = px.colors.sequential.matter_r,
    title="K-means clusters distribution"
    )
fig.show()

Comments on the k-plot above

The scatter plot above contradicts the elbow plot that we did earlier, and shows 2, or even 3 very clear clusters within our dataset.

Without the K-means model that we have just run, it would have been impossible for our sales department to figure this out.

Our next step is to try and determine what the principal components for determining these 3 clusters are. According to the PCA analysis below, we can quickly see that the main components are:

  1. "opera"
  2. "sports"
  3. "theatre"
In [32]:
# the last thing we can do, is try and understand why we have these clusters
# for this, we use Scikit Learn's decision tree class, which provides
# a feature importance evaluation method
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier()
dt.fit(X,labels)
for col,val in sorted(zip(
    X.columns, dt.feature_importances_),
    key=lambda col_val: col_val[1],
    reverse=True
):
    print(f"{col:10}\t{val:10.3f}")

# we had kept a copy of the dataframe under the name df_temp, and it's time to use it
df = df_temp.copy()

# filtering by users who like these activites
sports = df.loc[df["likesports"] == 1]
opera = df.loc[df["likeopera"] == 1]
theatre = df.loc[df["liketheatre"] == 1]
vegas = df.loc[df["likevegas"] == 1]
musicals = df.loc[df["likemusicals"] == 1]
jazz = df.loc[df["likejazz"] == 1]
broadway = df.loc[df["likebroadway"] == 1]
concerts = df.loc[df["likeconcerts"] == 1]
classical = df.loc[df["likeclassical"] == 1]
rock = df.loc[df["likerock"] == 1]

# creating a grouped by function
def getGroupBy(data,column):
    group = data.groupby(column,as_index=False).agg({"fullname":"count","total_paid":"sum","volume":"sum"})
    return group

# applying the function
grouped_sports = getGroupBy(sports,"likesports").rename(columns={"likesports":"type", "fullname":"count"})
grouped_opera = getGroupBy(opera,"likeopera").rename(columns={"likeopera":"type", "fullname":"count"})
grouped_theatre = getGroupBy(theatre,"liketheatre").rename(columns={"liketheatre":"type", "fullname":"count"})
grouped_vegas = getGroupBy(vegas,"likevegas").rename(columns={"likevegas":"type", "fullname":"count"})
grouped_musicals = getGroupBy(musicals,"likemusicals").rename(columns={"likemusicals":"type", "fullname":"count"})
grouped_jazz = getGroupBy(jazz,"likejazz").rename(columns={"likejazz":"type", "fullname":"count"})
grouped_broadway = getGroupBy(broadway,"likebroadway").rename(columns={"likebroadway":"type", "fullname":"count"})
grouped_concerts = getGroupBy(concerts,"likeconcerts").rename(columns={"likeconcerts":"type", "fullname":"count"})
grouped_classical = getGroupBy(classical,"likeclassical").rename(columns={"likeclassical":"type", "fullname":"count"})
grouped_rock = getGroupBy(rock,"likerock").rename(columns={"likerock":"type", "fullname":"count"})

# making some small changes
grouped_sports["type"] = grouped_sports["type"].astype(str)
grouped_opera["type"] = grouped_opera["type"].astype(str)
grouped_theatre["type"] = grouped_theatre["type"].astype(str)
grouped_vegas["type"] = grouped_vegas["type"].astype(str)
grouped_musicals["type"] = grouped_musicals["type"].astype(str)
grouped_jazz["type"] = grouped_jazz["type"].astype(str)

grouped_classical["type"] = grouped_classical["type"].astype(str)
grouped_rock["type"] = grouped_rock["type"].astype(str)
grouped_sports.at[0,"type"]="Sports"
grouped_opera.at[0,"type"]="Opera"
grouped_theatre.at[0,"type"]="Theatre"
grouped_vegas.at[0,"type"]="Vegas"

grouped_rock.at[0,"type"]="Rock"

# concat in Pandas does what UNION does in sql
plot = pd.concat([grouped_sports,
           grouped_opera,
           grouped_theatre,
           grouped_vegas,
           grouped_musicals,
           grouped_jazz,
           grouped_broadway,
           grouped_concerts,

           grouped_rock
           ], ignore_index=True)

Cluster analysis:

It clearly appears, using the bar plot above and the scatter plot below, that our main k-means cluster is determined by the "likesports" category.

As a business analyst, we really want to communicate this finding to our sales department:

  • Our customers who like sports show a very distinct purchasing behavior: they tend to buy less tickets, but they are ready to pay much more per ticket (see the scatter plot below).

# 2. Top 5 sellers by value (user name, first name, last name, user name, value and quantity sold) in New York.
df = getQuery(
"""
WITH t2 (userid, username, firstname, lastname, state) AS
    (SELECT userid, username, firstname, lastname, state FROM allusers)
SELECT TOP 5
    t2.username,
    t1.sellerid,
    CONCAT(t2.firstname, ' ', t2.lastname) AS full_name,
    SUM(t1.pricepaid) AS total_value,
    SUM(CAST(t1.quantitysold AS INT)) AS total_volume
FROM
    sales AS t1
    LEFT JOIN t2 on t1.sellerid = t2.userid
WHERE
    t2.state = 'NY'
GROUP BY 
    t2.username,t1.sellerid,CONCAT(t2.firstname, ' ', t2.lastname)
ORDER BY
    total_value DESC;
"""
    )
df

# 3. Top 5 buyers (user name, first name, last name, user name, value and quantity sold) overall by value and volume.

    (SELECT userid, username, firstname, lastname, state FROM allusers)

    t2.username,
    t1.buyerid,
    CONCAT(t2.firstname, ' ', t2.lastname),
    SUM(t1.pricepaid) AS total_value,
    SUM(CAST(t1.quantitysold AS INT)) AS total_volume

    sales AS t1

GROUP BY 
    t2.username,t1.buyerid,CONCAT(t2.firstname, ' ', t2.lastname)
ORDER BY
    total_value DESC;

    )

# 5. Most expensive ticket sold (price per ticket), who (buyers first & last name) bought this ticket? Who sold the ticket (sellers first & last name)? What was the event name and in which city was it hosted?
df = getQuery(
"""
SELECT TOP 5
    t1.priceperticket,
    t2.eventid,
    CONCAT(ISNULL(t4.firstname, 'unknown'), ' ', t4.lastname) AS buyer_name,
    CONCAT(ISNULL(t5.firstname, 'unknown'), ' ', t5.lastname) AS seller_name,
    t2.eventname,
    t6.venuecity
FROM
    listings AS t1
    LEFT JOIN allevents AS t2 ON t1.eventid = t2.eventid
    LEFT JOIN sales AS t3 ON t2.eventid = t3.eventid
    LEFT JOIN allusers AS t4 ON t3.buyerid = t4.userid
    LEFT JOIN allusers AS t5 ON t3.sellerid = t5.userid
    LEFT JOIN venue AS t6 ON t2.venueid = t6.venueid
ORDER BY
    t1.priceperticket DESC;
"""
    )
df
